Problem Statement (provided by Turing College)¶

Module 4: Deep Learning
=======================
Sprint 2: Natural Language Processing - Toxic comment challenge
---------------------------------------------------------------

The time has come again to put together all we learned in the previous lessons and try to tackle a real-life issue.

In this project, we will try to put ourselves into the shoes of content moderators. Every online platform which has an open forum faces an issue of people posting inappropriate comments, which if uncontrolled, can lead to loss of users, reputation and revenue. However, it is impractical and expensive for humans to keep track of all the messages other people post. Luckily, ML is here to help. We can train a model to automatically analyze all the messages users write and flag toxic users/comments so that appropriate actions can be taken.

We will use Kaggle toxic comment dataset <https://www.kaggle.com/c/jigsaw-toxic-comment-classification-challenge>

Your task today is to build a **multi-label** classifier, to assign forum posts to one or more of the 6 classes.

* * * * *

Multi-label classification
--------------------------

Up until now all, of the classification exercises we have seen were *multi-class* (e.g. dog, cat, plane) or binary (e.g. yes/no). Both methods are used when there is only 1 right answer, e.g. an animal cannot be both a dog and a plane. In *multi-label* classification, each input can result in many possible answers, e.g. articles could have a mixture of tags: news, sports, politics.

Source: https://theailearner.com/2019/07/15/multi-label-classification/

So what are the implications for the neural network, that you are going to build?

1. You cannot use softmax any more, since it makes a probability distribution over all of the classes. This time we need each output to have its own and independent probability. A good way to do it is to apply a Sigmoid activation to the output layer, which will squash your output between 0 and 1, thus you can treat the output as a probability to a sample belonging to a class
2. We need to change our loss function. Cross-entropy loss is used for multi-class problems, so you will have to change it to Binary Cross-entropy since we want each output considered individually.
3. Your labels will now have to be 1-hot-encoded. Since each output can have various labels, it is a good way to represent it. So a label, that belongs to class 1 and 4 out of possible 5, will be represented as `[0, 1, 0, 0, 1, 0]`. You can use sklearn [one-hot-encoder](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.preprocessing.OneHotEncoder.html) to easily convert your labels
4. When using model outputs (e.g. predictions in prod, evaluation), you will need to threshold the output. Why? Consider how a multi-label output with sigmoid activation from your model will look. For a 5 label problem, it will be a vector with 5 values, each from 0 to 1, e.g. `[0.01, 0.99, 0.68, 0.89, 0.32]`. How do you convert this into yes/no for each label? By applying a threshold of some value, such as 0.5. Meaning if the probability is less than 50%, we say it does not belong to this class. If more than 50% then it does, which will convert the above output to `[0, 1, 1, 1, 0]`

You can use HuggingFace transformers library and adapt a *{TRANSFORMER}*ForSequenceClassification method. I recommend using [DistilBERT](https://huggingface.co/transformers/model_doc/distilbert.html#distilbertforsequenceclassification) or [RoBERTa](https://huggingface.co/transformers/model_doc/roberta.html#robertaforsequenceclassification). You will have to make sure you don't pass labels to the classifier and calculate it yourself in the model.

def run_entire_notebook(filename: str = None):
    run_all = False
    if not run_all:
        print("skipping optional operation")
        fullpath = f"cached/printouts/{filename}.txt"
        if filename is not None and os.path.exists(fullpath):
            print("==== 🗃️ printing cached output ====")
            with open(fullpath) as f:
                print(f.read())
    return run_all

In [23]:
@cached_dataframes(gitignored=True)
def dataset_split():
    splits = split_utils.split_dataset(
        df=train_raw,
        target_cols=labels,
        split_sizes={"train": 0.70, "hp": 0.10, "val": 0.10, "test": 0.10},
        stratify_labels=False,
        rnd=42,
    )
    return {
        "train_X": splits["train"][0],
        "train_y": splits["train"][1],
        "hp_X": splits["hp"][0],
        "hp_y": splits["hp"][1],
        "val_X": splits["val"][0],
        "val_y": splits["val"][1],
        "test_X": splits["test"][0],
        "test_y": splits["test"][1],
    }

With this, the split is persisted to disk once the first time this notebook is run, and all future re-runs will reload the exact same split.

The splits are stored on disk and are consistent across system reboots. This is one way to guarantee that there will be no issues around accidental data leakage.

In [44]:
plot_letter_frequency(eng_freq.frequency - actual_frequency)

Findings:

  • $> 96\%$ of the letters are within $\pm 1.0\%$ of their theoretical frequency.
  • $> 80\%$ of the letters are within $\pm 0.5\%$ of their theoretical frequency.

Conclusion: It seems that the letter frequency might be "close enough" to english. But we might be fooling ourselves, trying to see things that are not there.

Let's do a quick check using Chi2.

$H_0$ = The observed letter frequencies in the comments column do not significantly differ from the expected frequencies of letters in the English language.

$H_1$ = The observed letter frequencies in the comments column significantly differ from the expected frequencies of letters in the English language.

Significance $\alpha = 0.05$

In [46]:

print(f"P-value: {p_val}")

Chi2 statistic: 0.04232933448492569
P-value: 1.0

We cannot reject $H_0$. p-value is 1.0, much larger than our $\alpha$. The differences are not significant enough to reject the null hypothesis.

The distributions seem "close enough" to what they should look like if all of the text was english language.

This does not prove that all/any of the comments are in English, but it allow us to not have to worry about this, for now.. (particularly useful when we get to embeddings and choosing a dictionary/word list)

def store_cached_dataset_to_csv():
    splits = dataset_split()

    for s in ["train", "hp", "val", "test"]:
        md(f"**storing {s} split**")
        X = splits[f"{s}_X"]
        y = splits[f"{s}_y"]
        xs = X.shape
        ys = y.shape
        after = X.join(y)
        aftershape = after.shape
        assert aftershape[0] == xs[0]
        assert aftershape[0] == ys[0]
        assert aftershape[1] == xs[1] + ys[1]
        print(s, aftershape)

        after = after[features + labels]
        after["labels"] = after[labels].values.tolist()
        after = after.drop(columns=labels)
        after.to_csv(f"dataset/splits/{s}.csv", index=False)  # =["id"])
        print(after.columns)
        print(after.iloc[5:10])

def load_comments_dataset() -> DatasetDict:
    dataset = load_dataset(
        "csv",
        data_files={
            "train": "dataset/splits/train.csv",
            "hp": "dataset/splits/hp.csv",
            "val": "dataset/splits/val.csv",
            "test": "dataset/splits/test.csv",
        },
    )

    for split in dataset.keys():
        dataset[split] = dataset[split].map(
            lambda e: {"labels": [float(x) for x in e["labels"][1:-1].split(", ")]}
        )

    return dataset

Training our model to detect toxic comments¶

In this section, we will train the downstream classifier so it is able to perform well in our task of interest.

Before doing this, we will want to optimize the configuration so that training is both effective and efficient.

This will require not exceeding the max GPU memory.

Configuring our training so it fits our resources¶

We tried various combinations of configurations but found that enabling FP16 contributes immensely to speeding up training.

Let this table compare just a couple of configurations done on the exact same PC

FP16 Training Batch Size GPU Memory Usage Training time Chosen configuration
False 8 10GB 5hr
True 12 8GB 3hr ⭐

Just from enabling FP16, which does not sacrifice model performance, and only adjusts float-precision when needed, we can see:

  • it allows for 50% larger batch size, improving training
  • while keeping a 20% smaller memory footprint
  • and almost 2x faster end to end training time

A quick "back of the envelope" calculation ${10 \over 8} * {5 \over 3} = 2.1$ factor of boost in performance

These values were just tweaked and adjusted on the fly. The main goal was to make sure that the training could complete without exceeding the GPU memory.

Since the entire training would take hours and it would complete overnight, I wanted to be conservative with the tweaking (taking 1hr longer is fine, but crashing at 3am and not completing would mean having to spend 5h the next morning retraining). This is why the memory was adjusted to be around 8GK instead of trying to max out the 12GB that the card has.

f, ax = plt.subplots(6, 2, figsize=(10, 24))

thresholds = np.arange(0, 1, 0.01)
num_labels = 6

optimal_thresholds = [0.52, 0.39, 0.5, 0.42, 0.35, 0.33]

for i in range(num_labels):
    row = i
    col = 0
    precisions, recalls, f1_scores = [], [], []
    for threshold in thresholds:
        preds = (sigmoid_outputs[:, i] > threshold).astype(int)
        precisions.append(precision_score(true_labels[:, i], preds))
        recalls.append(recall_score(true_labels[:, i], preds))
        f1_scores.append(f1_score(true_labels[:, i], preds))

    ax[row, col].plot(thresholds, precisions, label="Precision")
    ax[row, col].plot(thresholds, recalls, label="Recall")
    ax[row, col].plot(thresholds, f1_scores, label="F1 Score")

    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(true_labels[:, i], sigmoid_outputs[:, i])
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

    ax[row, col].set_xlabel("Threshold")
    ax[row, col].set_ylabel("Score")
    ax[row, col].set_title(f"Performance for [{labels[i]}]")
    auto_threshold = np.array(f1_scores).argmax() / 100
    ax[row, col].axvline(x=auto_threshold, color="purple")
    ax[row, col].axvline(x=optimal_thresholds[i], color="red")
    ax[row, 0].grid(True)
    ax[row, 0].legend()

    ax[row, 1].plot(fpr, tpr, label="ROC curve (area = %0.2f)" % roc_auc)
    ax[row, 1].plot([0, 1], [0, 1], label="baseline", color="grey")
    ax[row, 1].set_xlabel("FPR")
    ax[row, 1].set_ylabel("TPR")
    ax[row, 1].set_title(f"ROC curve [{labels[i]}]")
    ax[row, 1].legend()
    ax[row, 1].grid(True)

The high score on the ROC curve is likely caused by the major imbalance in the dataset (most comments are "non-toxic"), so the chart to correctly understand how the model performs are the ones on the left column (precision, recall, f1)

Performance Analysis¶

It seems that the model is fairly good at making predictions, but that it does suffer in cases where there is not enough data.

Just from the charts, we can easily identify the rare classes:

  • threat
  • identity_hate
  • and severe_toxic

We can see it from the lower performance, and we can also see it in the jagged line edges. The classes with more data show smoother lines.

We can also see that their threshold should be adjusted, in order to provide the best possible performance.

We have adjusted and plotted these optimal thresholds on top of the charts to visualize them better.

The red line shows the "manually configured" threshold, the purple line shows the "max f1 score".

We could look at other metrics (sklearn.metrics.precision_recall_fscore_support() comes to mind) that would allow us to customize the weight for accuracy and recall so it's not 50/50%. This will largely depend on the business needs (What is the cost for incorrectly labeling a comment as toxic? what is the cost for failing to identify those?) etc...

But for now, the out-of-the-box f1score seems good enough.

import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

f, ax = plt.subplots(6, 4, figsize=(15, 24))

thresholds = np.arange(0, 1, 0.01)
num_labels = 6

optimal_thresholds = [0.52, 0.39, 0.5, 0.42, 0.35, 0.33]

for i in range(num_labels):
    row = i
    col = 0
    precisions, recalls, f1_scores = [], [], []
    for threshold in thresholds:
        preds = (sigmoid_outputs[:, i] > threshold).astype(int)
        precisions.append(precision_score(true_labels[:, i], preds))
        recalls.append(recall_score(true_labels[:, i], preds))
        f1_scores.append(f1_score(true_labels[:, i], preds))

    ax[row, col].plot(thresholds, precisions, label="Precision")
    ax[row, col].plot(thresholds, recalls, label="Recall")
    ax[row, col].plot(thresholds, f1_scores, label="F1 Score")

    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(true_labels[:, i], sigmoid_outputs[:, i])
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

    ax[row, col].set_xlabel("Threshold")
    ax[row, col].set_ylabel("Score")
    ax[row, col].set_title(f"Performance for [{labels[i]}]")
    auto_threshold = np.array(f1_scores).argmax() / 100
    ax[row, col].axvline(x=optimal_thresholds[i], color="red")
    ax[row, col].grid(True)
    ax[row, col].legend()

    ax[row, 1].plot(fpr, tpr, label="ROC curve (area = %0.2f)" % roc_auc)
    ax[row, 1].plot([0, 1], [0, 1], label="baseline", color="grey")
    ax[row, 1].set_xlabel("FPR")
    ax[row, 1].set_ylabel("TPR")
    ax[row, 1].set_title(f"ROC curve [{labels[i]}]")
    ax[row, 1].legend()
    ax[row, 1].grid(True)

    optimal_preds = (sigmoid_outputs[:, i] > optimal_thresholds[i]).astype(int)
    cm = confusion_matrix(true_labels[:, i], optimal_preds, normalize="true")
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, ax=ax[row, 2], cmap="Greys_r")
    ax[row, 2].set_title(f"Confusion Matrix [{labels[i]}] %")

    optimal_preds = (sigmoid_outputs[:, i] > optimal_thresholds[i]).astype(int)
    cm = confusion_matrix(true_labels[:, i], optimal_preds)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, ax=ax[row, 3], fmt="d", cmap=ListedColormap(["white"]))
    ax[row, 3].set_title(f"Confusion Matrix [{labels[i]}]")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Summary¶

Executive Summary¶

This project explores using NLP and Transformers (BERT, in particular) to perform multi-label classification of wikipedia comments.

The dataset seems to be mostly in English, even thought there are some minor discrepancies in letter frequencies.

Part of the difficulty that this dataset provides is due to numerous typos, mispellings or malformed sentences. It's unclear whether these are intentionally typed poorly to try to confuse rudimentary text classification models.

Model Performance¶

The performance of this model is overall good on all data splits, showing that there is good generalization and minor overfitting.

Categories with lots of examples perform well (precision >= 80%, recall >= 80%). The only concerning areas around this model is the subpar performance for the rare classes (precision >= 50%, recall >= 50%), but we're confident that, given more data, the performance would be better.

We considered exploring data augmentation techniques, but some of the tools seemed unfit for the problem at hand. Some techniques require translating text to a new language, and then translating back, and this could prove difficult particularly when the text and threats might have been misspelled intentionally to bypass detection.

Improvements¶

Given more time, future work could investigate a few avenues:

  • Unsupervised Learning: Trying a less customized and more "out of the box" model
    • eg. It would be nice to try a HuggingFace Pipeline for Zero-Shot-Classification as seen in these videos.
    • This would basically be an unsupervised learning problem, so we would not be able to use it, but it would be nice nonetheless.
  • Data Augmentation:
    • eg. Trying different data augmentation techniques and see if any of them are robust to mispellings
  • Robustness to misspellings:
    • eg. Trying to use BERT (or another model) to detect misspelled words (Words that are Out of Vocabulary), and then try to make them replace them with properly spelled words, as part of the preprocessing.

Given the time constraints, none of these could be attempted, but it would be nice to see if any of these help overcome some of the data issues and improve the overall end to end performance.
